data.name: For The Love of God by Steve Vai
data.description: This mini-documentary features the world’s greatest stunt guitarist and supreme virtuoso, Steve Vai, as he tells the incredible story behind his signature song “For the Love of God.” Released in 1990, Vai wrote the piece on the fourth day of a ten day fast as he was striving to reach an altered state of consciousness. "For The Love Of God" was also voted No. 29 of the 100 greatest guitar solos of all time and has been featured in numerous video games including Guitar Hero III: Legends of Rock and Rock Band.

data.name: Faithfully by Journey
data.description: The story behind Journey's 1983 classic rock standard "Faithfully" that Neal Schon, Steve Perry and Jonathan Cain worked on together. The song, despite having no chorus, has become of the the bands most recognizable hits. It also gave Journey their second consecutive top 20 hit, influenced Prince’s “Purple Rain” and was the song Neal chose to play while proposing to his wife.

data.name: Alone by Heart
data.description: The background on Heart’s epic number one power-ballad "Alone" as told by Ann Wilson and songwriter Billy Steinberg. The groundbreaking song has a list of accolades, it was Heart's most successful UK single, hip the top 10 on the charts in over eight countries, has since been featured on multiple soundtracks, covered by Celine Dion, and named one of the best power-ballads of all time. "Alone" is truly an epic song.

data.description: Kevin Cronin shares the impetus behind REO Speedwagon’s classic song "Roll With The Changes." Released in 1978, the song hit Cronin in a flash while moving to LA. Learn how he wrote the lyrics on a brown paper bag while driving as he was literally rolling with the changes.

data.name: Right Now by Van Halen
data.description: Sammy Hagar reflects on Van Halen's 1992 single "Right Now" and how it the lyrics came from a place of higher consciousness, living in the moment, and not being afraid of change. This artistic approached pushed the envelope and challenged the stereotype of their band. While the more philosophical song was a change of pace for Van Halen, the music video won three MTV Music Video Awards, including the award for video of the year.
